title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Suppose we have two ordered fields <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{1}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{2}]]></fr:tex> which both have the <fr:link
type="local"
href="ca-0007.xml"
addr="ca-0007"
title="Least-Upper-Bound Property">Least-Upper-Bound Property</fr:link> and each contain the rational numbers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> as a subfield. Then there exists an order-preserving field isomorphism <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  R_{1}\to  R_{2}]]></fr:tex>, i.e., <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{1}]]></fr:tex> is isomorphic to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{2}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>Since the ordered field <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> with the LUB property and containing <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> is essentially unique, we refer to it as the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Real Numbers</html:dfn> and write it as <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
